#Q.5) I have decided to investigate the factors that effect the number of casualties through the road type and whether 
#     the numner of vehicles involved in the accident is correlated to the number of casualties or not
placeholder1 = accidents.groupby("Road_Type")["Number_of_Casualties"].sum()
placeholder1.plot(kind = "bar", label = "Casualties")
plt.xlabel("Road Type")
plt.ylabel("Number of Casualties")
plt.title("Comparison Between Number of Casualties and Road Type UK 2019")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

According to the "Road Safety Open Dataset Guide" spreadsheet provided from the UK government, the variable "Road_Type", is stored in code values, in this case each code corresponding to a specific road type. The road type:

1=Roundabout 2=One way street 3=Dual carriageway 6=Single carriageway 7=Slip road 9=Unknown 12=One way street/slip road -1=Data missing or out of range

As clearly shown from the bar chart above, the Road_Type=6 corresponding to single carriageway held the highest number of casualties by a very large significant margin. The road type single carriageway is defined as a road with 1, 2 or more lanes arranged as one singular carriageway in a manner where there is no central reservation to seperate opposing traffic flow.

Given that the single carriageway held the highest number of casualties by a very large margin, it is clear to the UK government that the single carriage road type is a very dangerous road type. Possible reasons why it may be considered dangerous, may be clear due to the defining features of the singe carriageway: 1 singular carraige way and no division between opposing traffic flow. From this data, it may be in the interest of the government and all drivers to either, reduce the number of single carriageways to reduce casualties or adjust the definition of single carriageways by, for example a division to seperate the opposing flow of traffic. These two possible solutions, will greatly reduce the number of casualties.

#Q.5) Continued:
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(accidents["Number_of_Vehicles"], accidents["Number_of_Casualties"])
corr, p_value = pearsonr(accidents["Number_of_Vehicles"], accidents["Number_of_Casualties"])
x = [accidents["Number_of_Vehicles"].min(), accidents["Number_of_Vehicles"].max()]
y = [slope * xx + intercept for xx in x]

plt.scatter(accidents["Number_of_Vehicles"], accidents["Number_of_Casualties"])
plt.plot(x, y, "-r")
plt.annotate("r=" + str(corr), xy=(10, 50), fontsize=10)
plt.xlabel("Number of Vehicles")
plt.ylabel("Number of Casualties")
plt.title("Comparison Between Number of Casualties vs Number of Vehicles UK 2019")
plt.show()

In this part of the answer, I aim to investigate the relationship between the number of vehicles involved in the accident against the number of casualties in the accident. It is hypothesized that the more vehicles involved in an accident the more casualties there will be due to the natural increase of parties in the accident.

I created a scatter plot to show the number of vehicles against the number of casualties. The scatter plot is relatively confusing as there are multiple identical pairs of data, for example at 1 vehicle, there were multiple rows of data that matched to 1 casualty. On top of that, this scatter plot also includes an anomaly at 1 vehicle with 52 casualties. However, it is inappropriate to omit the anomaly as it would interfere in the calculations of pearson's correlation between these two variables.

Moving on, visually not too much information can be extracted visually from the graph, aside from the fact how there is less concentration in casualties the more vehicles involved. However, this seems like a natural observation due to fact how accidents involving multiple vehicles are considered less likely.

If we omit visual observations and look at the regression line along with pearson's correlation we can see a postively sloped regression line along with a positive pearson's correlation r value. This proves the initial hypothesis, meaning that the more vehicles involved in the accident, the higher number of casualties, in other words the number of vehicles involved in an accident is proportional to the number of casualties in an accident. However, this relationship between the number of vehicles and casualties is relatively weak as the slope of the regression line is relatively flat along with the perason's correlation value being relatively close to 0.

For part B of the assignment regarding the dataset on measurements regarding measurements of individual's heights, weights, their age and sex, I decided to focus on the variables Weight and Height. Therefore, for part B of the assignement I have decided to explore the relationship between individual's weight and height by gender. This part of the assignment assumes that measurements for height and weight are in standardized units of cm and kg. Furthermore, in the "male" column a value of 1 is assumed to be male whilst a value of 0 is assumed to be female.

I plotted a total of 3 plots, "Weight vs Height for Both Sex", "Weight vs Height Males" and "Weight vs Height Females". All three plots showed relatively strong relationships between weight and height at the first glance. I originally, first tried to fit an exponential curve against the dataset instead of a linear curve, however this didn't turn out to be an appropiate fit. From all three regression lines, given the slope of the line, we can notice a strong relationship between weight and height. This assumption is relatively intuitive as naturally the taller an individual is the heavier the individual will weigh. This assumption is then further proven by the pearson's correlation values displayed on each plot. Plot "Weight vs Height for Both Sex" had r = 0.94(3sf), "Weight vs Height Males" had r = 0.95 and "Weight vs Height Females" had r = 0.92. All three r values are extremely close to 1 signifying a very strong relationship between weight and height, in other words weight and height are directly proportional-

Lastly, I tried to fit a multiple regression line with weight as the dependent variable and height and age as the independent variables. From the summary of the table, we see another very high r-squared value and high adjusted r-squared value. As the r-squared value is also very close to 1, which measures how well the model fits the data, it validates my previous statements. Furthermore, as this model also includes data regarding weight and age, it suggests that the same techniques can be applied to weight and age and a high accuracy models with significant insights can be extracted.

From the three plots plotted in part i of the question:

  1. A large concentration can be seen at extreme ends of the percentage, high frequencies were seen at either close to 0% or 100%. Meaning that customers were either 0% or close to 0% industrial/commercial or 100% or close to 100% industrial/comercial. If customers were not industrial/commercial this suggests that customers were domestic, which is what is shown in the first plot
  2. We see that the majority of customers use high transformer ratings at 500VA
  3. We see that the majority of customers use Grd Mtd Dist. Substation

From the correlations table, I noticed a few interesting observations: the following pairs had positive relationships, albiet the r values were very weak aside frome TOTAL_CUSTOMERS and LV_FEEDER_COUNT:

  • Transformer_RATING and TOTAL_CUSTOMERS
  • Transformer_RATING and Percentage_IC
  • Transformer_RATING and LV_FEEDER_COUNT
  • TOTAL_CUSTOMERS and LV_FEEDER_COUNT

This means that there is a clear relationship between the pair TOTAL_CUSTOMERS and LV_FEEDER_COUNT, which is intuitive as more feeders are required the more customers there are, whilst the relationship between the other pairs weren't as strong.

I also noticed the following pairs had negative relationships that were also all weak:

  • Percentage_IC and TOTAL_CUSTOMERS
  • Percentage_IC and LV_FEEDER_COUNT
    This negative reltionship shown by their r values of the pairs above are relatively confusing as the r value indicates that:
  1. The higher percentage of industrial/commercial, the lower the total customers, or vice verse. I'm going to assume this happens due to the fact how the variable Percentage_IC excludes domestic customers which is shifted into a new variable TOTAL_CUSTOMERS. If this assumption holds true, then it would intuitively explain the negative correlation.
  2. The higher percentage of industrial/commercial, the less feeders required. This can be intuitively explained due to the fact how the scale of industry and commercial is big hence requiring less feeders, as opposed to domestic where each flat/appartment floor may require different feeders.
